<paragraph id="353E61C2E721626D30BD1DEF12248C24" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A8FFA14AE480E99710036D2BC57A94B9" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">
<taxonomicName id="D76ACD125A1B8BFD86F01951CC36BD4D" authorityName="Laicharting" authorityYear="1784" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Saperda" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Saperda similis" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="similis">
<emphasis id="829CE5611F2B19DB79308AB226AD120C" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Saperda similis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rather rare but widespread species that is distributed from Europe to the Far East (
<bibRefCitation id="56400A6F8D863E4A4905A50F2CE3A750" author="Danilevsky, ML" journalOrPublisher="HSC, Moscow" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" publicationUrl="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" refId="B11" refString="Danilevsky, ML, 2017a. Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017] http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" title="Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017]" url="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" year="2017 a">Danilevsky 2017a</bibRefCitation>
). Although this species is ecologically associated with willows (
<bibRefCitation id="AE405942BD73F666D702C4A19EBE74BE" author="Cherepanov, AI" journalOrPublisher="Oxonian Press, New Delhi" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" refId="B6" refString="Cherepanov, AI, 1991b. Cerambycidae of northern Asia. Vol. 3, Lamiinae Part III. Oxonian Press, New Delhi" title="Cerambycidae of northern Asia. Vol. 3, Lamiinae Part III." year="1991 b">Cherepanov 1991b</bibRefCitation>
), according to 
<bibRefCitation id="E5C2C61B0C35A2CE2978A8F83BD23276" author="Sama, G" journalOrPublisher="Kabourek, Zlin" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" refId="B61" refString="Sama, G, 2002. Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals. Kabourek, Zlin" title="Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals." year="2002">Sama (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, it is probably monophagous on 
<taxonomicName id="03A1C51AA689F48E675F6023BC731744" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Salix caprea" order="Aplousobranchia" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="caprea">
<emphasis id="715BBCBFC97BEBA9E2D37F7B5F40A2D7" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Salix caprea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The larvae develop in thin stems and branches of willows that are still growing (
<bibRefCitation id="8ACFE1696C5F87C14903C8A83A2C6179" author="Cherepanov, AI" journalOrPublisher="Oxonian Press, New Delhi" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" refId="B6" refString="Cherepanov, AI, 1991b. Cerambycidae of northern Asia. Vol. 3, Lamiinae Part III. Oxonian Press, New Delhi" title="Cerambycidae of northern Asia. Vol. 3, Lamiinae Part III." year="1991 b">Cherepanov 1991b</bibRefCitation>
). The adults are active at dusk and during the night in June and July and can be found on their host plants (
<bibRefCitation id="58EDFF2939769606C54F79E95F19E07F" author="Sama, G" journalOrPublisher="Kabourek, Zlin" pageId="25" pageNumber="132" refId="B61" refString="Sama, G, 2002. Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals. Kabourek, Zlin" title="Atlas of the Cerambycidae of Europe and the Mediterranean Area. Vol. 1. Northern, Western, Central and Eastern Europe British isles and Continental Europe from France (excl. Corsica) to Scandinavia and Urals." year="2002">Sama 2002</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="45823E6F97B4F0541AE0C11253DB5B77" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">
A single larva in a pupal cell (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E7AD9B4833A9E25A3AA1FA1304083B06" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 9. Field photos of immature stages and habitats of typical Mongolian cerambycid species: A shrub of Caragana bungei, the host plant of Anoplistes and Chlorophorus species B Caragana leucophloea shrubs in semi-desert, the habitat of Anoplistes halodendri minutus C cross-section of larval feeding grounds of Anoplistes halodendri in Caragana stem D adults emergence holes of Anoplistes halodendri E larva of Saperda similis in its pupal cell F riverbank in light taiga, the habitat of S. similis G larva of Saperda scalaris H thick layer of cambium under the bark of broken birch trunk, the microhabitat of S. scalaris and Mesosa myops." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.739.23675.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/187662" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">9E</figureCitation>
) was found in the trunk of a recently dead willow 
<taxonomicName id="670E2E5B30372920326DAD85C42349E3" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Salix" order="Aplousobranchia" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="04AD204BAA8DF953651EFA3D4D4A8967" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. in the light taiga next to a river (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5D5C1429320079F5E1137959F905FA82" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 9. Field photos of immature stages and habitats of typical Mongolian cerambycid species: A shrub of Caragana bungei, the host plant of Anoplistes and Chlorophorus species B Caragana leucophloea shrubs in semi-desert, the habitat of Anoplistes halodendri minutus C cross-section of larval feeding grounds of Anoplistes halodendri in Caragana stem D adults emergence holes of Anoplistes halodendri E larva of Saperda similis in its pupal cell F riverbank in light taiga, the habitat of S. similis G larva of Saperda scalaris H thick layer of cambium under the bark of broken birch trunk, the microhabitat of S. scalaris and Mesosa myops." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.739.23675.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/187662" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">9F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
